	<Body>
		<Section>
			<SectionHead />
			<HTML>
				&lt;p&gt;
Although bladder infections are more common in women, men can get them, too. Signs and symptoms of bladder infection in men include:
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Frequent urination&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Strong, persistent urge to urinate (urgency)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Burning or tingling sensation during or just after urination (dysuria)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Low-grade fever&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Cloudy urine with a strong odor&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Blood in urine (hematuria)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
Common causes of bladder infection in men include:
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Enlarged prostate (benign prostatic hyperplasia, or BPH)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Kidney stones&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Abnormal narrowing of the urethra (urethral stricture), which may result from urethral catheterization, surgery, disease or infection&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
Treatment of a bladder infection depends on the cause, but typically includes antibiotics.
&lt;/p&gt;
			</HTML>
